{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501324"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:27:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1747"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1747"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.19,0.03,0.14,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96765"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1747"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1747"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79380"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"128"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12728"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1981"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45010"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96765","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96765"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old Indigenous man presents to the Emergency Department with chest pain that has been present for two days. He first noticed it shortly after arriving in Adelaide, following an eight-hour drive from Ceduna. The pain is centrally located, sharp and made worse by coughing. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes (last glycated haemoglobin 83 mmol/mol) and obesity. His only regular medication is metformin twice daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears comfortable. His pulse rate is 85/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are normal with no added sounds or rubs. Chest is clear to auscultation. An ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute bacterial pneumonia","Acute anteroinferior ST-elevation myocardial infarction","Acute rheumatic fever","Acute pulmonary embolism","Acute pericarditis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and ECG findings are most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pericarditis\u003C/strong\u003E. Pericarditis is often associated with viral infection, most commonly \u003Cem\u003ECoxsackievirus\u003C/em\u003E. Other causative viruses include \u003Cem\u003EEchovirus\u003C/em\u003E, Epstein-Barr virus and cytomegalovirus. The clinical course can be fairly benign, with pleuritic chest pain and mild fever sometimes being the only clinical features. Patients often report that the chest pain worsens when lying down and improves when leaning forward. Diagnosis is largely clinical, with diffuse ST elevation (usually concave upwards, as seen in this patient\u0027s case) being characteristic. A pericardial friction rub may be noted during auscultation and in severe cases, evidence of right heart failure due to constrictive pericarditis may be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute bacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pleuritic chest pain; however, this patient\u0027s clinical picture is too mild. Patients typically complain of productive cough, shortness of breath, high-grade fevers and rigors. None of these features are present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute anteroinferior ST-elevation myocardial infarction\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely. Although this patient has risk factors as an Indigenous man with type 2 diabetes and obesity, his presentation is atypical. Myocardial infarction typically causes dull, crushing chest pain with associated shortness of breath and diaphoresis. ST elevation in myocardial infarction is localised to a particular vascular territory rather than diffuse. Anteroinferior infarcts are rare because the anterior heart is usually supplied by the left coronary artery while the inferior region is supplied by the right coronary artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute rheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects younger Indigenous patients, particularly those living in overcrowded housing or with limited access to sanitation. It follows pharyngeal infection with \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E and causes pancarditis, migratory polyarthritis, Sydenham\u0027s chorea, erythema marginatum and subcutaneous nodules. Patients may report dyspnoea, but chest pain is uncommon. Examination typically reveals a heart murmur and ECG may show PR interval prolongation. This patient has no history of preceding throat infection and lacks the characteristic features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute pulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes acute-onset pleuritic chest pain, often with associated deep vein thrombosis. While this man has recently completed a long drive, he has no other obvious risk factors such as active malignancy or recent surgery. He has no dyspnoea or calf tenderness, and his examination is unremarkable. The most common ECG finding in pulmonary embolism is sinus tachycardia, which is not present.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pericarditis typically presents with pleuritic chest pain that worsens when lying flat and improves when leaning forward.","Diffuse, concave-upward ST elevation on ECG is characteristic of pericarditis.","Viral infection, particularly Coxsackievirus, is the most common cause of acute pericarditis in immunocompetent patients."],"references":["Imazio M, Gaita F, LeWinter M. Evaluation and treatment of pericarditis: a systematic review. JAMA.\u202f 2015 Oct;314(14):1498\u2013506"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1747"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18668"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18668","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18668"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afd049e8-dec8-450c-aa25-f3650175d938.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/afd049e8-dec8-450c-aa25-f3650175d938.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":566,"height":265}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:37:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T21:37:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1747"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96765"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"